## Project A: Forecasting US Energy Consumption

**Data:**

You are asked to predict the monthly US residential energy consumption for the next 2 years for the 'Short-Term Energy Outlook' using data from the US Department of Energy.

**Import:**

The US Department of Energy collects an impressive amount of data to support the energy industries. For this assignment use the monthly total energy consumed by the US residential sector. The webpage

<https://www.eia.gov/totalenergy/data/browser/index.php?tbl=T02.02>

contains monthly web tables, but an easier approach to getting the data into R uses the result of the 'Download' button to read the source data from the source CSV file.

```{r}
#| include: false
#| warnings: false
library(tidyverse)
library(scales)
library(table1)
```

```{r}
#| warning: false
energy <- read_csv("https://www.eia.gov/totalenergy/data/browser/csv.php?tbl=T02.02",
# names in first row, but the names aren't meaningful
                   col_names = c("MSN","Time","Res_Energy","label1","label2","label3"),
                   skip = 1) |>
  mutate(Res_Energy = parse_number(Res_Energy, na = "Not Available"),
         Time = ym(Time)) 
```

[***Problem 1. Why is `energy` tidy?***]{style="color:royalblue;"}

*Note:* Your answer will apply the 3 tidy data rules.

Yes, the dataset is tidy. There are three tenets of tidy dataset design including that each variable must have it's own column, each observation must have it's own row, and that each value must have it's own cell. There are not multiple values assigned to the same cell, each observation has it's own row and each variable has it's own column. While there are some missing values that it will be important to account for later and be aware of in the time section that represent yearly totals, this is a tidy dataset that we can get to work on.

```{r}
#| eval: true
  filter(energy, Time > "1991-12-31" & MSN=="TERCBUS") |>
  select(Time, Res_Energy) |>
  na.omit()
```

**Wrangling:**

This version of the `energy` dataset requires some wrangling before performing the analysis. Specifically the following tasks are required:

-   filter to the data in rows where `MSN` is `TERCBUS` (Total Energy Consumed by the Residential Sector in trillion Btu),

-   filter to current data (after 1991),

-   remove the annual total rows (`Time` is missing / `NA`).

-   only include the columns `Time` and `Res_Energy` columns, and

[***Problem 2. Edit the following code chunk to perform the required tasks.***]{style="color:royalblue;"}

```{r}
#| eval: true
energy <- energy |>
# filter to TERCBUS Total Energy Consumed by the Residential Sector
  filter(MSN=="TERCBUS") |>
# filter to "since the 90's"
  filter(Time > "1991-12-31") |>
# remove annual total rows (Time is NA)
  na.omit() |>
# keep just the Time and Res_Energy columns
  select("Time", "Res_Energy")

# take a look
tail(energy)
```

